				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">having a game rely on the lockout chip in the first place is completely unsensible</div>
<br />
<br />What's unsensible about it? All consoles had lockout chips installed in them, so there's no reason why a game can't take advantage of that.
<br />
<br />If Nintendo REALLY wanted to take advantage of the lockout chip, they could have hooked up the lockout chips in the CARTRIDGES to the ROM enable lines, effectively rendering them nonfunctional in any third-party (or de-chipped) consoles. It would, however, have made it impossible to release the toploader without the CIC.
<br />
<br />As I recall, several SNES games would not work unless they detected a working CIC within the console, and the same was true of some N64 games as well.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Quietust, QMT Productions
<br />P.S. If you don't get this note, let me know and I'll write you another.</div>
